==English==

===Adjectival Phrase===
'''on opposite sides of the barricades''' or (''rare'') '''on opposite sides of the barricade'''

#{{idiom}} of [[stark|starkly]] [[different]], [[opposite]] views on an issue

====Etymology====
The idiom has been in use for at least a century[http://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1908/jul/23.htm] [http://www.fmep.org/reports/special_reports/no10-winter2000/01-clinton_administration.html].  It probably derives from a literal observation of political protests, where government buildings were insulated with barricades, and the government was said to not represent the people because they and the people were ''on opposite sides of the barricades''.

====Synonyms====
*[[diametrically opposed]]

